            +subheader("First Screen: Search Bar")
            span.
              The first screen of the web app is for the user to search for the representatives, by address.
              It starts with header, with a description of GovContact and a hero image to display brand.
              The only interactable item is the search box to input an address.
            +img("final-result.png", "final")
            +subheader("Second Screen: All the Reps")
            span.
              The second half of the app is to display all the representatives' information in a card format, which was decided upon in the wireframe stage.
              Every representative is required to have atleast an email and phone number. A Twitter or Facebook handle will also be displayed.
            +img("final-result2.png", "final") 
        +section("User Testing")
            span.project-p.
                The web app was tested with 5 participants in an informal interview setting. Each participant explored the site on their own and was asked follow up questions.
                Testing the app revealed: 
            +list()
              +listItem("Filtering and Sorting Options")
                | Most participants spent a lot of time scrolling to learn about representatives. Every participant had some diffculty when asked to find a specific representative
                | A sorting or filtering option would help solve this usability issue.
              //- +listItem("Increase text size of links")
                | Another common usuability issue was that participants had trouble finding and hovering over links to contact information e.g. a Twitter handle. The root of the problem was the text size, as people tended to squint when hovering over a link. 
              +listItem("Web may not be right platform")
                | Most participants they were more likely to use a search engine if they were already on a browser. As a website, GovContact may not provide as much value.
              
